# Kairo Compiler Architecture

## Overview

Kairo is a statically typed systems programming language with full native bidirectional C++ interoperability. The compiler leverages Clang as a backend - Kairo source is lowered to C++ lexical tokens, fed into Clang's parser/sema/codegen pipeline, and linked via a wrapped LLD.

```
Kairo Source (.kro)          C++ Headers (.h/.hpp)
       |                            |
       v                            v
#--------------#            #------------------#
|  Kairo Lexer |            |  Clang parses    |
|  (SIMD, UTF8)|            |  headers → stubs |
#------#-------#            #--------#---------#
       v                             |
#--------------#                     |
| Preprocessor |                     |
| (macros,     |                     |
|  imports,    |                     |
|  conditionals|                     |
|  skip zones) |                     |
#------#-------#                     |
       v                             |
#--------------#                     |
| Kairo Parser |                     |
| → Kairo AST  |                     |
#------#-------#                     |
       v                             |
#----------------------#             |
| Kairo Sema           |◄------------#
|  - type resolution   |   (C++ symbol stubs inform
|  - trait checking    |    Kairo sema about available
|  - generic inst.     |    C++ symbols)
|  - AMT borrow check  |
|  - Code expansion    |
|  - C++ nodes tagged  |
|    as "deferred"     |
#------#---------------#
       v
#----------------------#
| Token Emitter        |
|  - walks Kairo AST   |
|  - emits clang::Token|
|    stream            |
|  - source locs map   |
|    back to .kro via  |
|    Clang SourceMgr   |
|  - C++ imports emit  |
|    #include tokens   |
#------#---------------#
       v
#----------------------#
| Clang Parser         |
|  - parses token      |
|    stream → Clang AST|
#------#---------------#
       v
#----------------------#
| Clang Sema           |
|  - full C++ type     |
|    checking          |
|  - overload res.     |
|  - template inst.    |
|  - concept checking  |
|  - ADL, SFINAE, etc. |
|  - errors remap to   |
|    Kairo source locs |
#------#---------------#
       v
#----------------------#
| Clang Codegen        |
|  → LLVM IR           |
#------#---------------#
       v
#----------------------#
| LLVM Passes          |
|  - optimization      |
|  - debug info (DWARF)|
#------#---------------#
       v
#----------------------#
| LLD (Kairo wrapper)  |
|  - Kairo demangling  |
|  - Kairo diag engine |
|    integration       |
#------#---------------#
       v
     Binary
```

---

## Stage Breakdown

### 1. Kairo Lexer

**Status:** Done (Stage 1 self-hosted implementation in progress)

- SIMD-optimized tokenization (40-150ns/token)
- UTF-8 support with fast validation
- Arena-allocated token buffers (`TokenBuffer<512>`)
- Immediate table for literal data (`IntData`, `StringData`, `MacroExpansionInfo`)
- `TkError` tokens for error recovery (parser can skip bad tokens without cascading)
- `SourceManager` tracks all files with SIMD line indexing

**Key types:** `Lexer`, `Token`, `TokenBuffer<N>`, `TokenKind`, `ImmediateTable`, `SourceManager`

---

### 2. Preprocessor

**Status:** Done (Stage 1 implementation in progress)

- Macro definition collection (parameterized, variadic, default args)
- Macro expansion with inside-out argument pre-expansion
- Rescan loop for nested macro invocations
- Cycle detection via `_active_macros` global chain (save/restore around arg expansion)
- Import resolution with trie-based directory indexing
- Conditional compilation via skip zones (`SkipList`)
- Scope tracking for module-qualified macros
- Builtin macros: `file!`, `line!`, `column!`, `count!`, `stringify!`, `unstringify!`, etc.
- `TkMacroExpand` token wrapping preserves expansion chain for diagnostics

**Key types:** `PreProcessor`, `MacroExpander`, `MacroDefinition`, `ImportProcessor`, `ImportResolver`, `SkipList`, `ScopeTracker`, `ExpansionContext`

---

### 3. Kairo Parser

**Status:** Not started

- Input: expanded token buffer from preprocessor
- Output: Kairo AST
- Error recovery: skip to next synchronization point on error (semicolons, braces, keywords)
- `TkError` tokens from lexer are skipped - don't cascade into parse errors
- Pratt parsing for expressions (precedence climbing)
- Reports diagnostics via `DiagEngine`

**AST node categories:**
- Declarations: `FnDecl`, `ClassDecl`, `StructDecl`, `EnumDecl`, `VarDecl`, `TraitDecl`, `ImplDecl`
- Statements: `ReturnStmt`, `IfStmt`, `WhileStmt`, `ForStmt`, `MatchStmt`, `BlockStmt`
- Expressions: `BinaryExpr`, `UnaryExpr`, `CallExpr`, `MemberExpr`, `CastExpr`, `LiteralExpr`
- Types: `BuiltinType`, `PointerType`, `ReferenceType`, `GenericType`, `CppOpaqueType`
- Special: `ImportCppDecl`, `DeferredCppExpr`

---

### 4. C++ Header Stub Extraction

**Status:** Not started

When the parser encounters `import cpp "header.h"`:

1. Invoke `libclang` to parse the header
2. Walk top-level declarations via `clang_visitChildren()`
3. Extract lightweight stubs - just enough for Kairo sema to not reject valid code
4. Insert stubs into Kairo symbol table under the appropriate namespace/module

**Stub structure:**
```
CppSymbolStub {
    name:         SymbolID
    qualified:    ModulePath        // namespace::class::name
    kind:         CppSymbolKind     // Function, Class, Struct, Union, Enum, Template, Namespace, Typedef, Variable
    is_template:  bool
    param_count:  i32               // -1 for overloaded/variadic (skip arity check, defer to Clang)
    is_pod:       bool              // for structs: safe for value-type semantics
    clang_type:   clang::QualType   // opaque handle, handed back during token emission
    source_file:  string            // which header
}
```

**Extraction scope (Tier 1):**
- Free functions
- POD structs/classes (fields + methods)
- Enums (with enumerator values)
- Typedefs/using
- Namespaces
- Global variables

**Deferred to Clang (no stub detail needed):**
- Template internals (just mark `is_template = true`)
- Overload sets (just mark `param_count = -1`)
- Operator overloads
- Multiple inheritance layouts
- constexpr/consteval evaluation

---

### 5. Kairo Sema

**Status:** Not started

Two responsibilities:
1. **Full checking** of Kairo-specific features (AMT, traits, generics)
2. **Stub validation** of C++ interop (symbol exists? roughly right arity? mark as deferred)

**What Kairo sema checks:**
- Kairo type resolution and inference
- Trait satisfaction / impl verification
- Kairo generic instantiation
- AMT / borrow checking (see §6)
- Kairo-specific semantic rules (e.g., `finally` blocks, pattern matching exhaustiveness)
- Basic validation of C++ calls: symbol exists in stub table, isn't wildly wrong

**What Kairo sema defers to Clang:**
- C++ overload resolution
- C++ template instantiation
- C++ concept/requires checking
- C++ implicit conversions
- C++ ADL (argument-dependent lookup)
- Anything involving C++ type internals

**AST annotation after sema:**
- Every node has a resolved type (Kairo type or `CppOpaqueType` handle)
- C++ interop nodes tagged with `DeferredCppCall` / `DeferredCppType`
- AMT annotations attached (borrow kind, lifetime, ownership) - erased during lowering

---

### 6. AMT (Advanced Memory Tracking) - Borrow Checker

**Status:** Not started (design phase)

Runs as a sub-pass of sema, after type resolution, before token emission.

**For pure Kairo code:** full borrow checking
- Ownership tracking (move semantics)
- Shared vs exclusive borrows
- Lifetime inference
- Dangling reference detection

**At C++ trust boundaries:**
- Verify Kairo-side borrows are valid at the call point
- Assume C++ doesn't violate them (can't prove otherwise)
- After C++ call returns, resume tracking
- Pointers returned from C++ are "untracked" unless annotated

**Ownership annotations for C++ interop:**
```
@cpp_owns      - C++ allocated, C++ frees. Kairo gets a borrow.
@kairo_owns    - C++ allocated, Kairo must free.
@shared        - Reference counted, both sides can hold.
```

**AMT erasure:** after borrow checking passes, all AMT annotations are stripped during token emission. The emitted C++ tokens have raw pointers/references. AMT is purely a compile-time check - zero runtime cost.

---

### 7. Token Emitter (Kairo AST → clang::Token stream)

**Status:** Not started (this is the core lowering layer)

Walks the Kairo AST and emits `clang::Token` objects into a token stream that Clang's parser consumes.

**Source location mapping:**
```cpp
// Create virtual file in Clang's SourceManager for each .kro file
auto &SM = clang_instance.getSourceManager();
auto fid = SM.createFileID(
    llvm::MemoryBuffer::getMemBuffer(kairo_source, "module.kro")
);

// Each emitted token gets a mapped location
// Kairo line 42, col 10 → clang::SourceLocation pointing into "module.kro"
auto loc = SM.translateLineCol(fid, 42, 10);
token.setLocation(loc);
```

This means Clang's diagnostic output automatically points to `.kro` source files with correct line/column. No error remapping needed for most cases.

**Lowering rules (Kairo construct → C++ tokens):**

```
Kairo                          C++ tokens
------------------------------------------------
fn foo(x: i32) -> i32          int32_t foo ( int32_t x )
var x: i32 = 5                 int32_t x = 5 ;
var x = 5                      auto x = 5 ;
class Foo { ... }              class Foo { ... } ;
struct Bar { ... }             struct Bar { ... } ;
if cond { ... }                if ( cond ) { ... }
if cond { a } else { b }      if ( cond ) { a } else { b }
for i in 0..10 { ... }        for ( int32_t i = 0 ; i < 10 ; ++ i ) { ... }
while cond { ... }             while ( cond ) { ... }
match expr { ... }             switch ( expr ) { ... }  (or if-else chain)
x as i64                       static_cast < int64_t > ( x )
ref!(T)                        T &
*T                             T *
import cpp "foo.h"             #include "foo.h"
module Foo { ... }             namespace Foo { ... }
trait Trait { ... }             (concept or vtable struct - TBD)
...args splice                 (variadic template expansion - TBD)
```

**C++ interop nodes:** when the emitter encounters a `DeferredCppCall` or `DeferredCppType`, it emits the original C++ tokens directly. Since the C++ header was `#include`d, Clang already knows about these symbols.

**Estimated size:** 2000-3000 lines for full language coverage. This is the most critical piece of novel engineering in the compiler.

---

### 8. Clang Pipeline (Parser → Sema → Codegen)

**Status:** Provided by Clang - no implementation needed

The emitted token stream is fed into Clang's standard pipeline:

1. **Clang Parser** - parses tokens into `clang::ASTContext`
2. **Clang Sema** - full C++ semantic analysis including:
   - Type checking
   - Overload resolution  
   - Template instantiation
   - Concept checking
   - ADL, SFINAE
   - Implicit conversions
3. **Clang Codegen** - lowers Clang AST to LLVM IR
4. **LLVM Passes** - optimization, debug info

Kairo invokes this by creating a `clang::CompilerInstance`, configuring it with Kairo's flags (mapped to Clang equivalents), and running the pipeline.

**Diagnostic capture:** Clang's `DiagnosticConsumer` is subclassed to intercept diagnostics and route them through Kairo's `DiagEngine`. Since source locations already point to `.kro` files (via the virtual file mapping in the token emitter), most diagnostics display correctly without remapping.

**Error remapping for cascade suppression:** when Clang reports an error on a deferred C++ node, the Kairo diagnostic consumer:
1. Identifies the `DiagCategory` (from the Clang diagnostic ID)
2. Poisons that category in the Kairo `DiagEngine` for the relevant scope
3. Subsequent related errors are suppressed

---

### 9. Linker (LLD Wrapper)

**Status:** Not started

Repackaged LLD with:
- Kairo symbol demangling in error output
- Integration with Kairo `DiagEngine` for clean linker error formatting
- Direct flag mapping from Kairo compiler flags to LLD flags

**Object file generation:** each Kairo source file (after Clang codegen) produces a `.o` file. C++ imports produce their own `.o` files from the included headers. LLD links everything together.

---

## Diagnostic Engine

### Architecture

```
Call Site (lexer/parser/sema/etc.)
       |
       v
  DiagBuilder (fluent API)
    .primary(range)
    .secondary(range)
    .fix(range, replacement, msg)
    .note(code, loc, msg)
    .emit()
       |
       v
  DiagEngine
    - cascade suppression (poisoned category+scope pairs)
    - error counting / limits
    - -Werror support
       |
       v
  DiagConsumer (interface)
    ├-- BasicDiagConsumer (terminal output)
    ├-- JSONDiagConsumer  (LSP / tooling)
    #-- CollectorConsumer (testing)
```

### Error Code Format

```
<category><3-digit code><severity>

Categories:
  S   - Syntax
  U   - Uncategorized
  C   - Code Generation
  M   - Memory
  R   - Resolution
  L   - Linker
  SC  - Semantic
  P   - Portability/Platform
  CL  - Lowering
  OPT - Optimization
  I   - Internal

Severities:
  I - Ignored
  R - Remark
  V - Verbose
  N - Note
  D - Debug
  W - Warning
  E - Error
  F - Fatal

Examples:
  SC001E - Semantic Error 001
  S042W  - Syntax Warning 042
  M003E  - Memory Error 003 (AMT violation)
```

### Cascade Suppression

Each diagnostic belongs to a `DiagCategory`. When an error fires, its category can be poisoned for a source scope. Subsequent errors in the same category and scope are suppressed. Different categories still fire independently.

Example: lexer error in a string → poisons `Lexical` for that scope → parser errors about malformed tokens in that region are suppressed → but type errors in unrelated code still fire.

---

## Type Mapping (Kairo ↔ C++)

### Primitive Types
```
Kairo     C++              Size
------------------------------
i8        int8_t           1
i16       int16_t          2
i32       int32_t          4
i64       int64_t          8
u8        uint8_t          1
u16       uint16_t         2
u32       uint32_t         4
u64       uint64_t         8
f32       float            4
f64       double           8
bool      bool             1
usize     size_t           platform
isize     ptrdiff_t        platform
```

### Pointer/Reference Types
```
Kairo              C++
--------------------------
*T                 T*
*const T           const T*
ref!(T)            T&
const ref!(T)      const T&
std::const_ptr<T>  const T*
```

### Standard Library Bridge
```
Kairo              C++                  Conversion
-------------------------------------------------
kairo::string      std::string          implicit (thin wrapper constructors)
kairo::vec<T>      std::vector<T>       implicit
kairo::map<K,V>    std::unordered_map   implicit
kairo::set<T>      std::unordered_set   implicit
```

Bridge types have implicit constructors/conversion operators so cross-language calls work without explicit casting.

### C++ Types in Kairo

User C++ types (anything not in the bridge table) are held as opaque `clang::QualType` handles in the Kairo symbol table. Kairo sema doesn't inspect their internals - it just verifies the symbol exists and defers to Clang for type checking.

---

## Build Order / Implementation Priority

```
Phase 1 - Foundation (current)
  ✅ Lexer (Stage 1 in progress)
  ✅ Preprocessor (Stage 1 in progress)
  🔨 Diagnostic Engine
  
Phase 2 - Frontend
  ○ Parser → Kairo AST
  ○ Basic Sema (Kairo-only, no C++ interop)
  ○ Token Emitter (trivial subset: fn, var, if, while, for)
  ○ Clang pipeline integration (verify round-trip)

Phase 3 - Language Features
  ○ Traits / interfaces
  ○ Generics
  ○ Pattern matching / match
  ○ Full expression coverage in token emitter

Phase 4 - C++ Interop
  ○ libclang stub extraction
  ○ Deferred sema for C++ symbols
  ○ import cpp support
  ○ Std library bridge types (string, vec, map)

Phase 5 - Memory Safety
  ○ AMT ownership tracking
  ○ Borrow checking (pure Kairo)
  ○ Trust boundary annotations for C++ calls

Phase 6 - Tooling
  ○ LLD wrapper with Kairo demangling
  ○ LSP server (klsp)
  ○ Formatter (kfmt)
  ○ Package manager (kpkg)
  ○ Build system (kbld)
```

